{{Curling positions}}

In [[curling]], the '''lead''' is the person who delivers the first two stones of the end for their team. On most teams, where the lead does not act as [[skip (curling)|skip]] or [[vice (curling)|vice]], the lead will sweep for each of their teammates. Because of the free-guard rule, which prevents leads from removing most of an opponents stones, leads are usually proficient at throwing guards and other draws, and throw few takeouts or other power shots.<ref>{{cite web|last=Weeks|first=Bob|title=Curling For Dummies Cheat Sheet|url=http://www.dummies.com/how-to/content/curling-for-dummies-cheat-sheet.html|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref> In some regions, such as [[Eastern Ontario]] and the [[Eastern United States]], the lead is responsible for determining who has hammer, using random selection, such as flipping a coin. However, in most regions, this is the responsibility of the [[third (curling)|third]]. 

